00:06:54.079 --> 00:07:01.399
So I think it probably, I mean, I don't know how many, how many of our attendees are from

00:07:01.399 --> 00:07:07.600
the insurance space or have kind of exposure to the insurance space, but I'll briefly go

00:07:07.600 --> 00:07:13.559
over the insurance space in general, sort of what are the various functions at an insurance

00:07:13.640 --> 00:07:23.640
company, how, how data, data management, data sciences can, can help in, you know, decision

00:07:23.640 --> 00:07:26.720
making at, at each of these functions.

00:07:26.720 --> 00:07:32.200
And then I'll, I'll jump briefly to sort of what has been a recent trends that we've been

00:07:32.200 --> 00:07:39.440
seeing in, in, in this space and cover the areas where innovation is happening and sort

00:07:39.440 --> 00:07:41.920
of where we see opportunities.

00:07:41.920 --> 00:07:50.799
So kind of going back to the basics, an insurance company, we, so in general, insurance is pooling

00:07:50.799 --> 00:07:51.799
of risks.

00:07:51.799 --> 00:07:57.119
So there needs to be measurement of risks to be able to ensure it.

00:07:57.119 --> 00:08:01.880
So I think that's typically the actuarial function within, within the insurance company

00:08:01.880 --> 00:08:10.279
is responsible for collecting data and then sort of defining and measuring risks and this

00:08:10.320 --> 00:08:16.239
I'm oversimplifying it, but this happens through sort of collecting a lot of data, collecting

00:08:16.239 --> 00:08:24.799
external data on and then actually sort of define actuarial assumptions, which are basically

00:08:24.799 --> 00:08:27.519
what are the risks that we're seeing with this particular product.

00:08:27.519 --> 00:08:32.159
So let's say if it's a life insurance product for a life insurance product, there are various

00:08:32.159 --> 00:08:33.159
types of risks.

00:08:33.159 --> 00:08:39.119
It could be modality risk, which is, you know, one of the primary risks with a, with a life

00:08:39.119 --> 00:08:46.239
insurance product, but also lapse risk and your premium persistency risks, risks that

00:08:46.239 --> 00:08:48.960
people who have signed up to pay premiums will not pay premiums.

00:08:48.960 --> 00:08:52.000
People who are sort of people will lapse out of policy.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:56.440
So these are various types of risks that each, each insurance product has.

00:08:56.440 --> 00:09:01.679
And I'm talking about risks from the perspective of the insurance company itself.

00:09:01.840 --> 00:09:09.599
And so like to study and measure each of these risks is, is a very data intensive process,

00:09:09.599 --> 00:09:18.119
as you can imagine, specifically if in a lot of situations, companies are lucky if they

00:09:18.119 --> 00:09:24.440
have prior data that they can rely their assumptions on, but in a lot of situations where a company

00:09:24.440 --> 00:09:27.960
is interested in launching a new, new type of product.

00:09:27.960 --> 00:09:33.479
So we're kind of offering new types of guarantees that has not, you know, that the industry

00:09:33.479 --> 00:09:39.119
has not seen before, or there are no prior examples for them in those situations, it's

00:09:39.119 --> 00:09:42.619
tough to have data to back your assumptions.

00:09:42.619 --> 00:09:49.880
So typically there are sort of a lot of data science use cases in that area, part of the

00:09:49.880 --> 00:09:58.679
work that, you know, Milliman does with, with a lot of our clients is to help them

00:09:58.679 --> 00:10:01.280
design these behavioral assumptions.

00:10:01.280 --> 00:10:06.200
And so we use a lot of machine learning models, we use sort of traditional statistical regression

00:10:06.200 --> 00:10:11.700
models to, to study, I would, I would say our, our usage is more on the traditional

00:10:11.700 --> 00:10:17.080
statistical side rather than sort of more machine learning oriented, because in, in

00:10:17.080 --> 00:10:26.559
general, actuaries typically want to understand sort of the drivers of risk and sort of put

00:10:26.559 --> 00:10:32.119
a formula to it rather than, you know, rather than sort of walking through a black box.

00:10:32.119 --> 00:10:39.200
So I'd say we, we typically sort of help companies decide these assumptions through the use of

00:10:39.200 --> 00:10:40.200
data science.

00:10:40.200 --> 00:10:45.760
That's primarily, you know, what I got started doing at Milliman, this was 10 years ago.

00:10:45.760 --> 00:10:50.159
Now, so that's the actuarial use case.

00:10:50.159 --> 00:10:52.460
Now there's multiple other things that happen.

00:10:52.460 --> 00:10:58.119
So once you have these assumptions of how, how modality risks would look like, there's

00:10:58.119 --> 00:11:06.400
typically actuarial modeling systems that actuaries use to, to sort of project these

00:11:06.400 --> 00:11:08.280
risks further down the future.

00:11:08.280 --> 00:11:14.119
So 30 years down the future, what are my, what are the results that I need?

00:11:14.119 --> 00:11:17.159
What is the presence value of the premiums that I'll get?

00:11:17.159 --> 00:11:18.159
Things like that.

00:11:18.159 --> 00:11:25.559
So actuarial modeling is another very deep area in actuarial studies and you know, typically

00:11:25.559 --> 00:11:29.400
my company helps with those, those types of models as well.

00:11:29.400 --> 00:11:31.479
Now, these are not machine learning models.

00:11:31.479 --> 00:11:33.119
These are cash flow projections models.

00:11:33.119 --> 00:11:39.679
So we're taking sort of some assumptions and the present state of, of the policies and

00:11:39.679 --> 00:11:45.520
then projecting them through various economic scenarios, you know, 10 years, 20 years down

00:11:45.520 --> 00:11:46.520
the future.

00:11:46.520 --> 00:11:53.559
So traditionally, I think that's also a very data intensive process, but I'd say there's

00:11:53.559 --> 00:12:01.359
less data science there in the traditional sense of what data science implies.

00:12:01.359 --> 00:12:05.479
It's more simulations, it's more, you know, projecting things.

00:12:05.599 --> 00:12:12.679
So I think insurance companies who have their own inbuilt actuarial modeling systems are

00:12:12.679 --> 00:12:17.000
a very, very big users of, of, of compute, of cloud compute.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:21.239
And so in each of these projections, there's, there's very large amounts of compute that's

00:12:21.239 --> 00:12:22.359
needed.

00:12:22.359 --> 00:12:29.359
So if you're aware about systems such as Integrate or, or Atlas or GGI Access, these are traditional

00:12:29.359 --> 00:12:33.119
systems that are used for cash flow projections.

00:12:33.119 --> 00:12:35.960
But more modern systems.

00:12:35.960 --> 00:12:42.760
So, you know, we started sort of doing, you know, some of, some of this work on, I think

00:12:42.760 --> 00:12:48.039
five, five, six years ago on, on our studio deposit connect platform.

00:12:48.039 --> 00:12:55.960
And I know that a number of our clients are, are thinking about using more modern database

00:12:55.960 --> 00:13:02.520
systems such as Databricks and Snowflake for, for doing actual projections.

00:13:02.520 --> 00:13:04.559
So yeah, that's, that's an interesting area.

00:13:04.559 --> 00:13:10.039
You can see sort of the, the innovation happening there.

00:13:10.039 --> 00:13:15.520
Now if you move away a bit from actuarial, there's underwriting.

00:13:15.520 --> 00:13:23.520
So I think the way risks are measured and sort of is, is through underwriting, there

00:13:23.520 --> 00:13:27.599
are underwriters within the insurance company and, and underwriting is, is a, is a great

00:13:27.599 --> 00:13:36.080
example of, of how data sciences is operationalized, used within an insurance company.

00:13:36.080 --> 00:13:41.280
In general, I work within the life and annuity space.

00:13:41.280 --> 00:13:49.599
So in the life and annuity space, underwriting is, as you can imagine, very data intensive.

00:13:49.599 --> 00:13:55.840
And typically in this space, there's lots of usage of third party data sets and like

00:13:55.840 --> 00:13:57.239
unstructured data sets.

00:13:57.880 --> 00:14:06.200
So companies might be relying on sort of RX data or, or prescriptions or, or, you know,

00:14:06.200 --> 00:14:09.679
medical history, financial history, those types of things that are typically obtained

00:14:09.679 --> 00:14:11.880
through third party companies.

00:14:11.880 --> 00:14:17.159
And then sort of using very advanced machine learning models to, to determine risks.

00:14:17.159 --> 00:14:23.320
I'd say the use of less traditional statistical models, but more sort of machine learning

00:14:23.320 --> 00:14:26.520
approaches is prevalent in the underwriting space.

00:14:26.599 --> 00:14:30.679
Typically, if you move away from the life and annuity space to the property and casualty

00:14:30.679 --> 00:14:35.799
space, that's where you see a lot of innovation happening in the underwriting space with the

00:14:35.799 --> 00:14:41.479
use of images and videos and, and sort of, you know, geospatial data and whatnot.

00:14:43.159 --> 00:14:48.359
So I think that's a very interesting area of underwriting where, you know, data science

00:14:48.359 --> 00:14:49.159
is very prevalent.

00:14:51.960 --> 00:14:56.039
I know when we talked years ago, you were sharing a little bit about some of the production

00:14:56.039 --> 00:14:57.239
Shiny applications.

00:14:57.799 --> 00:15:03.080
Does the, some of this tie into those projects, like when you're showing risk projections?

00:15:03.960 --> 00:15:04.280
Yeah.

00:15:04.280 --> 00:15:04.599
Yep.

00:15:04.599 --> 00:15:13.960
So Shiny is, is something that is, has been quite transformative for, for our, for our

00:15:13.960 --> 00:15:15.239
team at Milliman here.

00:15:16.919 --> 00:15:23.960
And in fact, some of the applications that we've developed on Shiny is is, is actually

00:15:23.960 --> 00:15:28.599
in production used by, you know, some of our clients to study their risks.

00:15:29.239 --> 00:15:36.679
This is, I would say in both areas, typically what we have done is we have put the results

00:15:36.679 --> 00:15:39.479
of the models that we develop on policyholder behavior.

00:15:40.039 --> 00:15:44.440
So things like how would people lapse out of their insurance policies?

00:15:45.479 --> 00:15:50.760
What are, what is the timing of when people will start withdrawing from their annuity

00:15:50.760 --> 00:15:51.640
contracts?

00:15:51.640 --> 00:15:56.520
So typically these are the models that we develop on, on a large amount of data that

00:15:56.520 --> 00:15:58.599
we collect from insurance companies.

00:15:58.599 --> 00:16:02.359
And then we allow these companies to visualize the model.

00:16:02.359 --> 00:16:10.039
So let's say you can visualize how, how are withdrawal rates or lapse rates within your

00:16:10.039 --> 00:16:12.440
own company versus in the industry.

00:16:12.440 --> 00:16:16.760
And that kind of gives you a sense of the type of risks that you're insuring and maybe

00:16:16.760 --> 00:16:19.159
some actual decisions to be made later.

00:16:19.719 --> 00:16:25.400
But yeah, so for those types of use cases where we're putting the results of a business

00:16:25.400 --> 00:16:30.599
process, like an actuarial modeling or policyholder behavior models, and then letting

00:16:30.599 --> 00:16:35.799
actuaries sort of play with that data through a, through a dashboarding setup.

00:16:35.799 --> 00:16:38.359
I think Shiny has been, has been quite helpful.

00:16:40.039 --> 00:16:45.719
We have tried other, other types of dashboarding platforms, but the flexibility that, that

00:16:45.719 --> 00:16:48.200
Shiny allows us is, is, is amazing.

00:16:48.200 --> 00:16:53.080
So one of the things, for example, is when companies want to look at their mortality

00:16:53.080 --> 00:16:57.080
data, they want to sort of define their own custom buckets.

00:16:57.080 --> 00:17:01.559
So some companies want to define buckets from 10 to 20, or maybe 10 to 20 is a wrong

00:17:01.559 --> 00:17:03.479
assumption, maybe 40 to 50 years old.

00:17:03.479 --> 00:17:08.040
But then some companies want to study their assumptions in five year thresholds of 40

00:17:08.040 --> 00:17:09.079
to 45.

00:17:09.079 --> 00:17:13.719
Now Shiny allows us to sort of programmatically set up these things in a, in a way that's,

00:17:14.520 --> 00:17:15.959
that's, that's quite natural.

00:17:16.520 --> 00:17:25.400
And in Shiny, you can also sort of generate UI components programmatically that, that

00:17:25.400 --> 00:17:31.479
I think we've found that functionality very, you know, amazing and kind of compared to

00:17:31.479 --> 00:17:35.880
sort of some of the other alternatives, which has W and Power BI.

00:17:35.880 --> 00:17:39.160
I think there's, there's, there's more flexibility here.

00:17:39.880 --> 00:17:44.280
So yeah, to answer your question, Rachel, we, we've used Shiny a lot in, in displaying

00:17:44.280 --> 00:17:52.119
the results of our, of our studies, but to what's the other extent in actual modeling

00:17:52.119 --> 00:17:59.959
also, when an actual model runs, these are thousands of economic scenarios of how, like

00:17:59.959 --> 00:18:02.119
what macroeconomic situations would be there.

00:18:02.119 --> 00:18:06.199
And then for each of these situations, there's a, there's a projection 30 years down the

00:18:06.199 --> 00:18:06.439
line.

00:18:07.160 --> 00:18:13.959
We've used Shiny to sort of let actuaries visualize the results of these, these projections

00:18:13.959 --> 00:18:14.359
also.

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:18.680
And I think that has been less of a use case though.

00:18:18.680 --> 00:18:26.199
The primary use case of Shiny is kind of, you know, letting customers sort of visualize

00:18:26.199 --> 00:18:30.599
the results of our data science models, such as policyholder behavior models.

00:18:30.599 --> 00:18:34.199
So I think that that has been a very good use case.

00:18:34.760 --> 00:18:35.319
Yeah.

00:18:35.319 --> 00:18:36.040
Thank you for that.

00:18:36.599 --> 00:18:42.520
I see Arsenis, you have a question in the chat, which is getting a lot of upvotes here

00:18:42.520 --> 00:18:43.160
right now.

00:18:43.160 --> 00:18:44.920
I want to jump into this one first.

00:18:46.760 --> 00:18:47.260
There you go.

00:18:48.520 --> 00:18:50.680
Thank you so much for, for joining us this morning.

00:18:50.680 --> 00:18:51.400
And thank you, Rachel.

00:18:52.599 --> 00:18:53.079
Yeah.

00:18:53.079 --> 00:18:54.920
My question is actually kind of high level.

00:18:54.920 --> 00:18:58.920
It's a little bit broad, but being in, you know, in your industry, it's a pretty good

00:18:58.920 --> 00:19:03.719
intersection and given what you do, it's about the intersection of statistics and data science.

00:19:03.719 --> 00:19:09.000
So my question was, have you noticed that newer data scientists, as you might know,

00:19:09.800 --> 00:19:14.439
you know, for the last like 20 years, anybody who's a data scientist now probably came from

00:19:14.439 --> 00:19:15.560
another field.

00:19:15.560 --> 00:19:20.680
So are you finding that newer, that data scientists now that are minted data scientists

00:19:20.680 --> 00:19:27.239
have those degrees that they have sufficiently strong backgrounds in statistics to keep up

00:19:27.239 --> 00:19:28.280
with actuaries?

00:19:28.280 --> 00:19:35.640
Or are you finding that the two fields are kind of becoming distinct enough that, that

00:19:35.640 --> 00:19:40.839
it makes the search process for candidates a little bit different?

00:19:42.599 --> 00:19:44.839
Yeah, that's, that's, that's a great question.

00:19:47.079 --> 00:19:50.599
In, so our, our team has both actually.

00:19:50.599 --> 00:19:53.959
So we have traditionally actuaries.

00:19:53.959 --> 00:20:00.760
So actuaries are folks who, you know, study statistics and it is, it is their training,

00:20:00.760 --> 00:20:08.280
professional training to, to sort of fit new types of distributions into statistical models.

00:20:10.119 --> 00:20:15.640
And the, our team also has data scientists who are sort of from the other side of the

00:20:15.640 --> 00:20:15.880
lens.

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:21.719
Some of them have studied hard sciences and kind of transitioned to, to the data science

00:20:21.719 --> 00:20:27.800
field, or some actually have in the last 10 years, there's been, there's been a lot

00:20:27.800 --> 00:20:32.439
of, you know, university programs that have structured training around data science that

00:20:32.439 --> 00:20:39.479
has some of the folks that we have seen come from those programs are, are, are quite ahead

00:20:39.479 --> 00:20:44.760
in terms of, you know, their skill sets, the value that they bring to the table.

00:20:45.560 --> 00:20:54.040
So I would say some of these university programs and sort of, I'm sure POSIT has done a lot

00:20:54.040 --> 00:20:55.479
in terms of data science education.

00:20:56.920 --> 00:21:01.000
I think that has really helped in terms of the quality of candidates that we've been

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:05.959
seeing, but going back to your question in terms of the actual skill set, in terms of

00:21:05.959 --> 00:21:11.319
statistics, statistics, and then how data science, newer data scientists compare to

00:21:11.319 --> 00:21:22.280
those, I'd say traditionally actuaries do spend time with a lot of parametric models.

00:21:22.280 --> 00:21:25.479
So things like traditional regression techniques.

00:21:26.199 --> 00:21:32.920
And I mean, one of the advancements that we have seen in this space and in the space of

00:21:32.920 --> 00:21:38.280
policyholder behavior model from the last year was when we started using penalized

00:21:38.280 --> 00:21:44.599
regressions and, and you can imagine that is penalized regression is as old as time.

00:21:44.599 --> 00:21:49.800
I don't know since when people are sort of using lasso regression and whatnot, but it

00:21:49.800 --> 00:21:55.640
is only recent when actuaries started using those types of techniques to, to study and

00:21:55.640 --> 00:21:58.520
quantify policyholder behavior risks.

00:21:58.520 --> 00:22:03.959
So the actual profession, but because of all the regulations and the SOPs surrounding it

00:22:03.959 --> 00:22:05.079
is very slow moving.

00:22:05.800 --> 00:22:14.199
There's, there's lots of approaches to do, you know, a certain workflow, but actuaries

00:22:14.199 --> 00:22:18.839
are very limited by sort of, you know, their experience and in terms of the regulations,

00:22:18.839 --> 00:22:22.439
they're, they're limited by things that they, they want to try and do.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:34.199
I'd say the data scientists are more sort of excited and more, more, they bring the

00:22:34.199 --> 00:22:39.239
machine learning side of things more to the table, which has been, you know, quite, quite

00:22:39.239 --> 00:22:41.959
useful for, for some of our, some of our work.

00:22:43.319 --> 00:22:47.800
So for example, I talked about policyholder behavior models in the context of penalized

00:22:47.800 --> 00:22:48.439
regressions.

00:22:50.520 --> 00:22:55.079
I remember that, you know, a data scientist on our team has kind of taken that and put

00:22:55.079 --> 00:23:02.599
it into a tree-based model and sort of also that led to quite, quite some insights around

00:23:02.599 --> 00:23:09.319
sort of which, which additional variables are important to predict, predict that outcome.

00:23:09.959 --> 00:23:16.680
So I'd say data scientists are more faster moving or more sort of keeping up with the

00:23:16.680 --> 00:23:24.680
latest trends in the actual models and sort of statistical models and actuaries are doing

00:23:24.680 --> 00:23:25.800
the catch-up game now.

00:23:30.040 --> 00:23:30.520
Thank you.

00:23:31.160 --> 00:23:36.119
I see Bill and Libby both asked some, two questions around the third-party data.

00:23:36.119 --> 00:23:43.719
So maybe I'll try, I'll combine these a little bit, but Bill's question was like,

00:23:43.719 --> 00:23:48.680
what percentage of data is like, or do you purchase package data?

00:23:49.319 --> 00:23:51.560
Is open government data useful?

00:23:51.560 --> 00:23:56.119
And then to add on to that, Libby asked, is there a vetting process for purchasing third

00:23:57.079 --> 00:23:58.199
party data?

00:23:58.199 --> 00:24:00.359
Because I imagine it's a huge investment.

00:24:00.359 --> 00:24:03.880
So how do you ensure it's going to be valid and useful for your needs?

00:24:05.479 --> 00:24:06.280
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:24:09.319 --> 00:24:17.719
For, so something that we've, an initiative that our team was working on in the past year

00:24:17.719 --> 00:24:25.000
was to, so all, all the data that we have corresponding to how policyholders use their

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:28.920
policies, that's a longitudinal data.

00:24:28.920 --> 00:24:31.800
So you have like for one person, you have an entire history.

00:24:31.800 --> 00:24:38.439
Now we wanted to use that data set, condense down to one row, one row for each policyholder

00:24:38.439 --> 00:24:41.000
and then try to develop a propensity to buy a model.

00:24:41.640 --> 00:24:48.599
So who is, for example, one of the questions that we're going to answer is which type of

00:24:48.599 --> 00:24:55.400
customers are prone to buy a GLWBs or a policy with lifetime benefits guarantees.

00:24:57.000 --> 00:24:59.479
And we want to understand those customers better.

00:24:59.479 --> 00:25:04.199
And in terms of answering these questions, I'd say actuarial and insurance, the data

00:25:04.199 --> 00:25:06.599
that is there within the insurance company is limited.

00:25:07.160 --> 00:25:12.280
So we have to rely on sort of third party data to understand their behaviors better.

00:25:13.079 --> 00:25:20.680
I would say something that we have found useful is, is partnering up with, some traditional

00:25:20.680 --> 00:25:21.640
data aggregators.

00:25:21.640 --> 00:25:29.000
Now, usually data, there are these data aggregator companies that sort of work with open source

00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:35.319
data or sort of data that is open out in the world and they scrape it or they have partnerships

00:25:35.319 --> 00:25:38.119
with sort of various data sellers.

00:25:38.520 --> 00:25:43.479
And something that we have found useful is that when we work with one data aggregator,

00:25:44.119 --> 00:25:48.520
then sort of we get to sort of play with various types of data sets they have.

00:25:48.520 --> 00:25:53.880
Some of these data sets might have restrictions in terms of how we can use it.

00:25:53.880 --> 00:25:59.880
So, for example, with the recent, I mean, there's a lot of regulation in this space

00:25:59.880 --> 00:26:02.760
and it's been growing as we speak.

00:26:03.079 --> 00:26:05.160
It's been growing as we speak.

00:26:05.160 --> 00:26:17.640
So we cannot really make a decision on who to send a marketing communication to based

00:26:17.640 --> 00:26:20.599
on, like we cannot make an individual decision.

00:26:20.599 --> 00:26:27.400
I think that's restricted by a local CCPA, the California Consumer Privacy Act.

00:26:29.319 --> 00:26:30.839
So we do it on a group level.

00:26:31.560 --> 00:26:35.880
So I think there's restrictions in terms of how we use this third party data.

00:26:36.599 --> 00:26:45.079
But, yeah, going back to the question, the vetting process is through select, you know,

00:26:45.079 --> 00:26:48.599
some of these companies offer match rates.

00:26:48.599 --> 00:26:53.880
So some of these companies have like fuzzy matching and, you know, we can sort of send

00:26:53.880 --> 00:26:59.479
them some anonymized information and they can send us fuzzy matching rates.

00:27:00.199 --> 00:27:04.920
As you can imagine, like some of the names do not match a lot of times and addresses

00:27:04.920 --> 00:27:05.319
don't match.

00:27:05.319 --> 00:27:07.560
So we don't know if we're getting the right data or not.

00:27:07.560 --> 00:27:14.280
So there's various types of fuzzy matching algorithms that some of these data aggregators

00:27:14.280 --> 00:27:20.520
have that we tend to use to sort of figure out what is the amount of matching that we

00:27:20.520 --> 00:27:26.920
can get in terms of sort of what's getting the useful data.

00:27:26.920 --> 00:27:28.599
So I think that's the vetting process.

00:27:29.560 --> 00:27:36.439
But in terms of how we use it, yeah, I think there's various types.

00:27:36.439 --> 00:27:39.560
I've described the marketing use case and underwriting for sure.

00:27:39.560 --> 00:27:45.319
There's RX providers, there's like various companies.

00:27:45.319 --> 00:27:51.479
Milliman has a practice called IntelliScript, which is, I think, one of the largest underwriting

00:27:51.479 --> 00:27:53.319
data providers in the U.S.

00:27:54.040 --> 00:28:00.119
And, you know, we have connects with sort of various health data providers and everything

00:28:00.119 --> 00:28:06.520
and a very elaborate pipeline to sort of obtain that data, clean that data and sort of make

00:28:06.520 --> 00:28:08.040
a product out of it.

00:28:08.040 --> 00:28:14.439
So yeah, being a data aggregator is a hard business.

00:28:14.439 --> 00:28:16.920
We have worked with a lot of data aggregators in the past.

00:28:17.640 --> 00:28:23.880
It is not easy to sort of form those data relationships and get those data sets.

00:28:23.880 --> 00:28:32.280
But those who have those relationships have an edge in terms of sort of, you know, the

00:28:32.280 --> 00:28:34.680
value that they can provide to insurance companies.

00:28:34.680 --> 00:28:38.040
Yeah, thank you.

00:28:38.040 --> 00:28:41.079
And I mean, you just mentioned IntelliScript as well.

00:28:41.239 --> 00:28:50.280
So thinking about all this data across the company, do you collaborate with other departments

00:28:50.280 --> 00:28:51.560
to share data across?

00:28:53.640 --> 00:29:02.839
Yeah, I think Milliman traditionally is a very peculiar in the way that it is.

00:29:04.839 --> 00:29:06.439
IntelliScript is a Milliman practice.

00:29:07.239 --> 00:29:11.959
My own practice, which is called Life and Amity Predictive Analytics, LAPA, is also

00:29:11.959 --> 00:29:13.000
a Milliman practice.

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:20.839
But these are different Milliman practices, but these are all very, very decentralized.

00:29:20.839 --> 00:29:25.000
These are, you can think of them as kind of separate companies entirely.

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:35.319
But kind of under the broader Milliman umbrella that, so I think we have interacted with

00:29:35.319 --> 00:29:39.319
IntelliScript in the past and, you know, data science applications on sort of risk

00:29:39.319 --> 00:29:41.000
models, risk modeling.

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:51.800
But IntelliScript's business is selling sort of the data that they have and sort of allowing

00:29:52.359 --> 00:29:54.920
companies to underwrite using that data.

00:29:54.920 --> 00:30:00.920
So you can imagine that their biggest asset, biggest revenue generator is the quality of

00:30:00.920 --> 00:30:06.839
that data itself and sort of the risk score that insurance companies can derive on a policy

00:30:06.839 --> 00:30:08.359
basis based on this data.

00:30:09.560 --> 00:30:16.199
And in this situation, as you can imagine, and I imagine that's true for data aggregators

00:30:16.199 --> 00:30:19.160
also, they're very productive about their data.

00:30:19.160 --> 00:30:28.920
And so once the value is proven for that data, they don't want to let sort of other companies

00:30:28.920 --> 00:30:30.359
evaluate the quality of data.

00:30:30.359 --> 00:30:35.640
It's not so much out in the world to sort of evaluate as such, because they don't want

00:30:35.640 --> 00:30:40.599
to open themselves to the risk of sort of data evaluation and kind of comparison with

00:30:40.599 --> 00:30:42.199
other alternative data sets.

00:30:43.560 --> 00:30:46.520
Proving that value initially is hard enough.

00:30:46.520 --> 00:30:51.640
So once that is proven, I think they're quite productive of that data and sort of who they

00:30:51.640 --> 00:30:53.719
share with that data with.

00:30:53.719 --> 00:30:57.160
So I'd say, yeah, we've worked with some applications, but yeah, I think that's a

00:30:57.160 --> 00:30:59.319
totally separate business also.

00:30:59.319 --> 00:31:06.839
OK, yeah, I'm just from the community aspect, I'm always so curious to hear how big companies

00:31:06.839 --> 00:31:11.319
work together when there's different pockets of data people all over the place.

00:31:11.959 --> 00:31:18.359
But I see Santiago asked some follow up questions around Shiny, and I know you put an asterisk

00:31:18.359 --> 00:31:20.040
there, so I'll ask it.

00:31:20.040 --> 00:31:23.400
But Santiago, if you want to jump in at any point, feel free.

00:31:24.680 --> 00:31:29.079
But the question was, for the Shiny apps that you put into production, how do you

00:31:29.079 --> 00:31:31.400
handle load multiple users?

00:31:32.199 --> 00:31:38.119
The question is, is it load balance or auto scaling taken care of by a platform like AWS

00:31:38.119 --> 00:31:41.640
or Connect, or is it something else like different packages?

00:31:42.520 --> 00:31:43.959
Yeah, yeah, good question.

00:31:43.959 --> 00:31:52.599
So I think when we started doing Shiny applications, we used Shiny server open source.

00:31:52.680 --> 00:31:55.560
That was back in 2016, I'd say.

00:31:56.359 --> 00:32:03.160
And then we needed authentication because as companies are giving us this data, they

00:32:03.160 --> 00:32:11.479
want to ensure that their data is safeguarded and that it is backed by best practices in

00:32:11.479 --> 00:32:15.319
terms of security and authentication, access control, et cetera.

00:32:15.959 --> 00:32:21.239
So we decided to move to using Shiny server professional edition then.

00:32:22.920 --> 00:32:31.560
And for authentication, we used Auth0 to sort of work with Shiny.

00:32:33.479 --> 00:32:42.040
But in terms of right now, I think our tech stack is we use Posit Connect to host these

00:32:42.040 --> 00:32:45.959
applications and then Auth0 again to sort of authorize access to these.

00:32:45.959 --> 00:32:51.640
But yeah, I think in terms of Shiny, that's what our tech stack is.

00:32:51.719 --> 00:32:53.880
I kind of forgot, what was the point of this question?

00:32:55.479 --> 00:32:56.760
Yeah, let me go.

00:32:56.760 --> 00:33:03.079
There were a few in it, but it was also just talking about handling the load in multiple.

00:33:03.079 --> 00:33:03.800
Okay, yeah, yeah.

00:33:03.800 --> 00:33:05.000
Sorry, I didn't touch on that.

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:12.839
So in terms of load, I think something that we've found useful is like our SDET team sort

00:33:12.839 --> 00:33:18.680
of after every release that the release is coordinated through Azure DevOps.

00:33:18.680 --> 00:33:22.359
And so that's where code is pushed to GitHub.

00:33:22.359 --> 00:33:25.079
And then automated deployment happens through Azure DevOps.

00:33:26.040 --> 00:33:33.479
Before we obtain a final approval on the production deployment, our testing team does

00:33:33.479 --> 00:33:38.839
regression tests, integration tests, and a load test sort of also.

00:33:38.839 --> 00:33:46.680
And load tests are, I do remember a package that was quite useful in load testing Shiny.

00:33:46.680 --> 00:33:47.959
I think it was Shiny load tests.

00:33:48.680 --> 00:33:54.040
And so Shiny test, Shiny load test is something that we've used in the past.

00:33:54.040 --> 00:34:01.000
But I think at this point, our testers are probably using things like Selenium to just

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:10.520
run multiple hits on the site and kind of see the responsiveness of the graphs and charts.

00:34:11.320 --> 00:34:17.639
For example, through one of these load tests, we ended up optimizing our snowflake queries

00:34:17.639 --> 00:34:20.439
that are used to generate these graphs.

00:34:20.439 --> 00:34:23.320
So I think load tests were quite useful there.

00:34:23.320 --> 00:34:33.479
But we're lucky also because our applications are not used 24-7, the load is not that much.

00:34:34.199 --> 00:34:38.760
Actually, we tend to use it when it's an actual assumption setting cycle.

00:34:38.760 --> 00:34:40.840
So that's certain times in the year.

00:34:41.479 --> 00:34:47.080
But during those times in the year, yeah, we can have like five people at the same time

00:34:47.080 --> 00:34:47.879
using the site.

00:34:47.879 --> 00:34:56.520
So it helps using things like Shiny load test and then frameworks like Selenium to automate

00:34:56.520 --> 00:34:57.479
load tests.

00:35:00.600 --> 00:35:01.000
Yeah, yeah.

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:06.840
So I mean, I just saw a follow-up question on Selenium.

00:35:06.840 --> 00:35:15.719
I think something that our testers do is develop a Selenium framework independent of the Shiny

00:35:15.719 --> 00:35:17.479
and R packages.

00:35:17.479 --> 00:35:19.959
And this is primarily written in Python.

00:35:19.959 --> 00:35:27.399
And they can probably just hit the site and hit various UI components and kind of test

00:35:27.399 --> 00:35:31.320
changing the inputs and see the responsiveness of the graphs and charts.

00:35:31.320 --> 00:35:35.639
So you can do that through a UI framework like Selenium.

00:35:35.639 --> 00:35:37.879
You don't have to use Shiny load test.

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:41.320
I see Edgar had a follow-up question.

00:35:41.320 --> 00:35:42.439
Edgar, do you want to jump in?

00:35:44.600 --> 00:35:45.159
Hi, yeah.

00:35:46.040 --> 00:35:53.239
So for the SQL queries that you mentioned that you optimized, were you using SQL directly

00:35:53.239 --> 00:35:54.120
into the Shiny app?

00:35:54.120 --> 00:35:58.360
Or was that initially like through dbPlyer and then you realized that you needed something

00:35:58.360 --> 00:35:58.679
better?

00:35:59.800 --> 00:36:02.679
dbPlyer is amazing.

00:36:02.679 --> 00:36:07.959
That's when I think we ended up starting with using dbPlyer.

00:36:08.760 --> 00:36:13.800
But then I feel like this might not reflect the current state of things on dbPlyer.

00:36:13.800 --> 00:36:20.199
It might have received a lot of updates, but five years back or so, we started using direct

00:36:20.199 --> 00:36:27.399
queries to Snowflake rather than using dbPlyer because we saw some avenues of optimization

00:36:27.399 --> 00:36:37.000
in terms of timing of, or even sort of how the queries run on Snowflake, separating that

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:40.199
into various parts and chunks rather than using dbPlyer.

00:36:40.199 --> 00:36:44.840
So I think we needed that flexibility more at that point of time.

00:36:44.840 --> 00:36:49.879
But since then, I feel like, I don't want to speak a lot of dbPlyer, I feel like it

00:36:49.879 --> 00:36:53.320
might have received a lot more updates and might be good for our use case now.

00:36:53.320 --> 00:36:58.040
But since then, we've stuck at using SQL queries directly on Snowflake.

00:36:59.080 --> 00:36:59.560
Thank you.

00:36:59.560 --> 00:37:06.360
Yeah, usually dbPlyer is going to improve, but it's going to be up to a certain point,

00:37:06.360 --> 00:37:06.679
right?

00:37:06.679 --> 00:37:11.479
Once you want something in production, you probably want to just optimize it yourself,

00:37:11.479 --> 00:37:15.800
but it does make sense that you use SQL directly.

00:37:15.800 --> 00:37:16.120
Thank you.

00:37:16.600 --> 00:37:25.639
I know you touched on the process your team goes for for deploying where you have, maybe

00:37:25.639 --> 00:37:29.879
it's a staging environment or where people are doing testing.

00:37:29.879 --> 00:37:35.080
And I realized that's a question a few customers have asked me about because different companies

00:37:35.080 --> 00:37:37.399
use so many different processes for this.

00:37:38.520 --> 00:37:41.320
And people often ask, like, what's best practice?

00:37:42.199 --> 00:37:46.840
And I was just wondering, could you talk a little bit more about what that looks like

00:37:46.840 --> 00:37:47.719
at your organization?

00:37:48.439 --> 00:37:49.000
Oh, sorry.

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:50.760
Best practices for what?

00:37:50.760 --> 00:37:56.919
Well, you mentioned the way that when you deploy, you have this like testing environment

00:37:57.560 --> 00:38:02.199
and some customers will ask for best practices there.

00:38:02.199 --> 00:38:02.360
Yeah.

00:38:02.360 --> 00:38:05.159
And I was just wondering what process to follow.

00:38:05.959 --> 00:38:06.199
Yeah.

00:38:06.199 --> 00:38:13.959
So I think because of the heavy regulation and the data protection,

00:38:17.560 --> 00:38:23.879
sort of our security posture has to adhere to sort of our contracts with companies who

00:38:23.879 --> 00:38:27.000
give us data for studying policyholder behavior.

00:38:28.439 --> 00:38:33.800
And some of these companies are very large, brick and mortar insurance companies, they

00:38:33.800 --> 00:38:38.439
have very elaborate security contracts.

00:38:38.439 --> 00:38:46.280
So I think what we have done and what we found useful is we've started getting a SOC 2 type

00:38:46.280 --> 00:38:50.840
2 audit almost four years back, three years back now.

00:38:51.479 --> 00:38:56.360
And as part of that audit, we need to have a formal release process.

00:38:57.000 --> 00:39:03.000
And our release process keeps on evolving and changing according to the needs.

00:39:03.000 --> 00:39:07.000
But I can describe it as there's a development server.

00:39:07.000 --> 00:39:14.919
So it's traditionally like a positive connect or sort of a studio terminal.

00:39:14.919 --> 00:39:15.800
It's not a server.

00:39:15.800 --> 00:39:19.719
It's on a shared desktop machine, Windows server.

00:39:19.719 --> 00:39:21.239
That's where development happens.

00:39:21.239 --> 00:39:26.520
And developers push those updates to the GitHub site.

00:39:26.520 --> 00:39:33.239
So there's traditionally three branches that develop beta and then actually for release

00:39:33.239 --> 00:39:34.760
candidate and prod.

00:39:35.479 --> 00:39:39.080
And traditionally how things sort of go in that manner.

00:39:39.080 --> 00:39:48.360
So once there's a push to the develop branch, there's good rules that kind of creates pull

00:39:48.360 --> 00:39:55.320
requests to sort of have another developer review that code, sort of see, do

00:39:56.760 --> 00:40:02.760
like not look at it on the server itself, but maybe just look at the code that was added

00:40:02.760 --> 00:40:03.879
and kind of approve it.

00:40:04.600 --> 00:40:10.360
And once we have that, then it goes through the, then the develop server can keep kind

00:40:10.360 --> 00:40:12.760
of having a lot of updates, right?

00:40:12.760 --> 00:40:14.199
Without being pushed to a release.

00:40:14.199 --> 00:40:17.399
So once we're ready to do a release, it goes to a beta stage.

00:40:18.120 --> 00:40:24.199
And on the beta server, there's like, there's developer reviews, but also there's a formal

00:40:24.199 --> 00:40:25.479
review from the testing team.

00:40:25.479 --> 00:40:28.679
So the testing team runs that automated test suit.

00:40:28.679 --> 00:40:29.879
If it's a new feature.

00:40:29.879 --> 00:40:35.800
So in Shiny, you can probably add, maybe we added a separate section of the web app.

00:40:35.800 --> 00:40:37.399
So there's no automated tests for that.

00:40:38.840 --> 00:40:45.239
So we end up doing sort of manual tests there to sort of see if any other feature breaks

00:40:45.239 --> 00:40:46.520
or how the load is.

00:40:47.800 --> 00:40:50.679
And then, so that's around the beta.

00:40:50.679 --> 00:40:54.760
Once we're sort of fine with the beta stage, we push to release candidate.

00:40:54.760 --> 00:41:01.399
Release candidate is maybe just to sort of check business functionality and load testing

00:41:01.399 --> 00:41:03.320
also happens on the release candidate stage.

00:41:03.320 --> 00:41:09.639
And that kind of leads to a production deployment.

00:41:09.639 --> 00:41:15.879
In each of these stage for our SOC 2, we need to sort of capture approvals, produce them

00:41:15.879 --> 00:41:16.679
for audits.

00:41:16.679 --> 00:41:25.080
And so our auditors make sure that every code push or every release is kind of thoroughly

00:41:25.080 --> 00:41:27.320
vetted and tested.

00:41:28.520 --> 00:41:30.600
So that's typically how the release cycle is.

00:41:30.600 --> 00:41:34.199
Now, in some releases, in some situations, we may end up doing a hot fix.

00:41:34.199 --> 00:41:36.840
So that's a branch off of a production.

00:41:36.840 --> 00:41:40.520
And then we push directly to production, then bring that change back to develop.

00:41:41.399 --> 00:41:42.760
There can be rapid releases.

00:41:42.760 --> 00:41:48.199
So there's situations where we need to put up something quite soon, let's say for a conference

00:41:48.199 --> 00:41:53.399
or for a call or for a demo, then that has a separate release cycle.

00:41:53.399 --> 00:41:58.040
But in general, most updates go through sort of this release cycle.

00:41:59.479 --> 00:41:59.959
Thank you.

00:41:59.959 --> 00:42:01.239
It's super helpful.

00:42:01.239 --> 00:42:05.560
And release cycle is the term that was not coming to mind when I was asking that.

00:42:06.760 --> 00:42:11.800
Brian, I see you asked a question around collaboration across the team.

00:42:11.800 --> 00:42:12.919
Do you want to jump in here?

00:42:18.280 --> 00:42:19.080
Can't hear you.

00:42:19.080 --> 00:42:20.679
Yes, sorry.

00:42:20.679 --> 00:42:22.520
I was trying to get my thing going here.

00:42:23.560 --> 00:42:31.800
Yeah, so I think collaborating with a team in these contexts of data science, you know,

00:42:31.800 --> 00:42:37.879
you see a lot of stuff with regard to agile processes and stuff from a software development

00:42:37.879 --> 00:42:38.679
perspective.

00:42:38.679 --> 00:42:44.120
But a lot of that seems to fall short when you're talking data science contexts, because

00:42:44.120 --> 00:42:50.520
there's a lot more experimentation and a lot more kind of gray areas as to what the next

00:42:50.520 --> 00:42:51.080
task is.

00:42:51.080 --> 00:42:56.199
And I was wondering if you have contended with that and how you've approached that in

00:42:56.199 --> 00:42:56.760
your teams.

00:42:58.360 --> 00:42:59.159
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:42:59.159 --> 00:43:09.320
So in terms of model development, I feel like it was back when we started developing these

00:43:09.320 --> 00:43:14.919
shiny applications, we started following the agile methodology.

00:43:14.919 --> 00:43:21.399
You know, I'd say we don't typically sort of stick to it all the time.

00:43:21.399 --> 00:43:28.600
But as a general sort of North Star, I think that's what we try to do is to sort of push

00:43:28.600 --> 00:43:36.120
updates faster, sort of, you know, and, you know, have incremental updates and, you know,

00:43:36.120 --> 00:43:41.159
push things faster, but then sort of push hard fixes if needed.

00:43:41.159 --> 00:43:50.199
But that also, you know, sometimes it doesn't align with sort of the actual profession at

00:43:50.199 --> 00:43:53.879
all, because everything needs to be tested before we put things out.

00:43:53.879 --> 00:43:59.479
So we need to sort of vet things before we sort of put it on.

00:43:59.479 --> 00:44:09.800
So sometimes the agile methodology sort of converts to a waterfall process for our software

00:44:09.800 --> 00:44:10.360
development.

00:44:10.360 --> 00:44:13.080
But I think your question is in terms of our modeling.

00:44:13.080 --> 00:44:23.080
In terms of models, I think something that we've followed is I wouldn't say it's agile,

00:44:23.080 --> 00:44:29.719
but in that, so there's a process where we try to improve our behavior models.

00:44:29.719 --> 00:44:36.439
And in that process, there's various types of new variables that we want to try and see

00:44:36.439 --> 00:44:37.719
if that is a good predictor.

00:44:38.360 --> 00:44:41.479
And so that's a cyclical process in there.

00:44:41.479 --> 00:44:46.120
And that doesn't quite align to the agile way of developing and deploying.

00:44:46.919 --> 00:44:53.639
So I feel like we've tried to sort of educate ourselves about the modern machine learning

00:44:53.639 --> 00:44:59.719
operations, MLOps methodologies and sort of stick to it.

00:44:59.719 --> 00:45:06.280
So in terms of we've used something like MLflow, I think there's an internal proof of concept

00:45:06.280 --> 00:45:12.280
going on on MLflow where part of our team is trying to use MLflow to track a lot of these

00:45:12.280 --> 00:45:18.199
experiments, track how adding these variables would affect let's say lapses or withdrawals,

00:45:19.959 --> 00:45:25.239
and then kind of have a nice dashboard to compare the results of all of these experimentation.

00:45:25.879 --> 00:45:32.520
And only after there's a decision on sort of what the actual parameters would look like

00:45:32.520 --> 00:45:40.120
that we go to sort of the next stage, which is sort of the fitting testing stage.

00:45:40.199 --> 00:45:47.800
And at that point, we also bring in a holdout data set to sort of test the models.

00:45:49.719 --> 00:45:52.760
There is a testing data set that is deployed right on the website.

00:45:52.760 --> 00:45:55.159
So that's not part of the training.

00:45:55.159 --> 00:46:00.760
So we let our customers see the results of that model right on the testing data set when

00:46:00.760 --> 00:46:01.399
it is deployed.

00:46:02.120 --> 00:46:07.639
But in terms of development, yeah, so that's usually our process is going to spend a lot

00:46:07.639 --> 00:46:14.520
of time in that experimentation stage, build some internal apps that help us to sort of

00:46:14.520 --> 00:46:16.919
visualize the results of that experimentation.

00:46:18.280 --> 00:46:21.239
It's hard to put a good word to sort of that process.

00:46:21.239 --> 00:46:27.639
I feel like we've been trying to educate ourselves about various advancements in the MLOps space

00:46:27.639 --> 00:46:32.439
to sort of leverage all that.

00:46:32.439 --> 00:46:34.840
But yeah, it's a continuous process.

00:46:35.719 --> 00:46:41.159
So much innovation happening within the MLOps space is that it's hard to keep track of.

00:46:44.199 --> 00:46:49.399
I see Neil had asked a question a little earlier that was, you mentioned that in the actuarial

00:46:49.399 --> 00:46:51.639
space, there's a lot of innovation.

00:46:51.639 --> 00:46:54.840
What do you think are the conditions that allow for innovation?

00:46:54.840 --> 00:46:57.320
And how do you encourage this as a company?

00:46:58.199 --> 00:46:58.840
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:46:58.840 --> 00:47:09.080
So I think I'd reframe that statement and say there's a lot of potential scope for innovation

00:47:09.080 --> 00:47:10.360
in the actuarial space.

00:47:10.919 --> 00:47:19.080
I would still say that it is a comparatively slower moving space because of age old practices

00:47:19.080 --> 00:47:25.719
and sort of, I think there's also regulations, there's lots of standard operating procedures

00:47:26.600 --> 00:47:27.959
that actuaries need to follow.

00:47:28.679 --> 00:47:35.239
There's standards of practices that are there for virtually every activity in an actuarial

00:47:35.239 --> 00:47:38.040
space like reserving valuations, pricing.

00:47:38.040 --> 00:47:42.280
There's very strict guidelines on what actuaries should do and should not do.

00:47:42.919 --> 00:47:48.760
So that kind of restricts sort of a lot of trying out new methods.

00:47:49.479 --> 00:47:54.360
But I think what we've been trying to do in the space we're trying to get into is

00:47:56.120 --> 00:48:02.679
sort of use more modern methods and modern machine learning approaches to behavior modeling.

00:48:03.479 --> 00:48:08.520
We're opening up to sort of using some of the modern data platforms,

00:48:08.520 --> 00:48:14.520
like their princess and snowflakes to sort of work on actuarial modeling.

00:48:16.439 --> 00:48:22.760
I feel like the driver of innovation in this space is primarily because, I mean,

00:48:23.560 --> 00:48:25.479
it is a data oriented space.

00:48:25.479 --> 00:48:28.600
There's a lot of data that actuaries work with.

00:48:28.600 --> 00:48:35.239
And as you can imagine, advancement in the data management and data sciences space is

00:48:37.239 --> 00:48:38.520
very rapid at this time.

00:48:38.520 --> 00:48:41.639
So I think actuaries are, as I said, doing the catch up game right now.

00:48:41.639 --> 00:48:45.959
We're trying to modernize our methods, use more modern data platforms.

00:48:45.959 --> 00:48:52.679
I think the innovation starts from the data platform itself before we move to data science.

00:48:53.639 --> 00:49:00.040
A lot of these processes are in Excel files, which sometimes can become quite large,

00:49:00.040 --> 00:49:04.280
very hard to keep track of, to ocean control, et cetera.

00:49:04.280 --> 00:49:11.000
So in the life analogy space, the innovation starts from sort of moving away from those older

00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:13.639
Excel file based methods to more modern methods.

00:49:13.639 --> 00:49:20.360
You're leveraging cloud and Jupyter notebooks and Python and R.

00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:27.560
In the modeling space, if you move away from data management to modeling,

00:49:27.560 --> 00:49:33.560
I feel like there's increasing innovation happening in terms of using advanced methods,

00:49:33.560 --> 00:49:39.320
advanced deep learning methods to study policyholder behavior using third party data.

00:49:39.320 --> 00:49:44.439
And as you sort of bring in more third party data, there's various deep learning approaches.

00:49:44.439 --> 00:49:49.159
So if you're using image or sort of forms to inform your underwriting models,

00:49:49.159 --> 00:49:51.399
then a lot of innovation is happening there.

00:49:53.479 --> 00:49:58.679
So yeah, the other driver of innovation that I've been seeing is generative AI.

00:49:59.959 --> 00:50:03.320
At least in the traditional brick and mortar companies, a lot of companies want to leverage

00:50:03.320 --> 00:50:10.679
generative AI and they need to fix their data situation first to be able to use gen AI methods.

00:50:11.239 --> 00:50:16.040
So a lot of scope, a lot of innovation is happening there in terms of modernizing

00:50:16.040 --> 00:50:17.560
the data management platform.

00:50:18.439 --> 00:50:22.360
So yeah, I think those are kind of the traditional drivers

00:50:23.000 --> 00:50:28.199
of innovation that we've been seeing in the actual real space.

00:50:31.719 --> 00:50:35.959
I've been meaning to ask you this, and when you mentioned Excel, it just reminded me.

00:50:36.600 --> 00:50:40.840
Someone had recently reached out from another insurance company,

00:50:40.840 --> 00:50:44.199
and they're working with a group of Excel users.

00:50:45.399 --> 00:50:50.360
They want to maybe inspire to start to use data science for some of their workflows.

00:50:51.879 --> 00:50:55.560
And I guess I'll just say this broadly, they were interested in connecting with

00:50:55.560 --> 00:50:57.800
others in the insurance space who have done this.

00:50:58.760 --> 00:51:04.360
But I was just wondering, should you have any thoughts on that or how it's worked?

00:51:04.840 --> 00:51:05.340
Yeah.

00:51:05.959 --> 00:51:11.159
Excel is a great tool for quick, dirty ad hoc work, right?

00:51:11.159 --> 00:51:15.159
And it's quick to sort of prove concepts and you can...

00:51:17.959 --> 00:51:20.600
The flexibility that it brings is kind of unparalleled.

00:51:20.600 --> 00:51:22.040
You don't have to do any setup.

00:51:22.040 --> 00:51:26.600
It's all self-contained and can handle considerably large amount of data.

00:51:26.600 --> 00:51:29.080
It kind of gives you the tool to do these things.

00:51:29.080 --> 00:51:33.159
But when you're dealing with very large amounts of data or when you need to have

00:51:34.919 --> 00:51:42.840
governed processes, I think that's when we found that there's a need to move away from Excel.

00:51:42.840 --> 00:51:47.479
So for example, a lot of companies use Excel for actual real assumption setting.

00:51:47.479 --> 00:51:53.800
And these are very large Excel files with hundreds of graphs in them and pivot tables.

00:51:54.520 --> 00:51:56.919
And it's hard to keep track of.

00:51:56.919 --> 00:52:02.760
And it takes 15 minutes sometimes to sort of open one of these files.

00:52:02.760 --> 00:52:09.399
And so there's a case to be made to move away from Excel, at least for situations where

00:52:09.399 --> 00:52:15.239
there's a large amount of data and there needs to be a governed process to deploy the results

00:52:15.239 --> 00:52:17.320
of whatever is being done in that Excel.

00:52:18.760 --> 00:52:22.360
So I think that's been the driver of the movement away from Excel.

00:52:22.360 --> 00:52:30.120
But I think you'd be surprised at a very large amount of companies sort of still using Excel

00:52:30.120 --> 00:52:34.199
in some of these very large processes like assumption setting.

00:52:34.199 --> 00:52:36.679
Or I would be surprised even actual modeling.

00:52:38.280 --> 00:52:43.639
But as the data size increases, as they're kind of brought under scrutiny by regulators, et cetera,

00:52:46.120 --> 00:52:49.959
that's the push to move away from Excel to use some of the modern methods.

00:52:52.439 --> 00:52:52.919
Thank you.

00:52:52.919 --> 00:52:54.919
I know we just have a few minutes here.

00:52:55.879 --> 00:52:58.120
And the hour always goes by so quickly.

00:52:58.679 --> 00:53:07.639
But I was just I meant to ask earlier to just to learn a little bit more on your career journey.

00:53:07.639 --> 00:53:12.360
So I know you went from data scientist to director of technology at Milliman.

00:53:12.360 --> 00:53:15.800
And before we go, I'm wondering if you could share any advice with us

00:53:16.520 --> 00:53:19.719
here for people who are looking to grow within their organizations.

00:53:20.439 --> 00:53:29.080
Well, yeah, I think I mean, it was probably 10 years ago when sort of there was

00:53:29.800 --> 00:53:33.560
it is probably true right now there's lots of opportunities to sort of make

00:53:35.159 --> 00:53:39.000
make impact if you're if you're good with data within an organization.

00:53:40.120 --> 00:53:46.919
Something that I found useful for my own career mobility is to be flexible in terms of how to

00:53:46.919 --> 00:53:50.040
provide that business impact.

